english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of Six Pines
  author: Shin Gae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the summer of the year Dingwei, I was banished to Jiangyin County. At that time, a severe drought had seized the land—gold melted and earth burned. After departing on my journey, the triple-fold heat intensified, and the entire world beneath heaven became like a bellows-fanned furnace. When the sun climbed high, even travelers vanished from the roads. Yet the attending official drove me forward relentlessly, and I stumbled on through the scorching exhaustion. Upon reaching the county, I lodged in a commoner's house—cramped and squalid, where stifling vapor proved even more poisonous than the open road. Flies, gnats, and bedbugs swarmed and tormented me. Soon I fell ill, and for more than ten days I lay moaning upon my bed. All who saw me grieved for me, saying: "West of the county stands the home of a good family. Though modest, it has a pine grove behind it where cool breezes gather." Straightway I moved there. The master received me warmly and seated me beneath the pines. The shade was dense, the air refreshing, and a clear breeze suddenly swept through—the flies and gnats vanished as if banished. My very bones seemed to awaken and return to life. From that day, my illness gradually mended.

    I then resolved to build a small shelter for sleeping and protection from rain and dew. Materials were scarce, so I used the straight branches as pillars and bent limbs as rafters, thatching the roof with reeds and screening the sides with mugwort. Day and night I dwelt there in ease and wandering leisure, indulging only what pleased my heart. I ceased to envy grand mansions and nearly forgot my own former home.

    One day the master said to me: "North of my house stands a ridge—not towering, yet the four horizons spread wide and flat around it, a true meeting place of all eight winds. I once wished to build a pavilion at its summit to shelter from rain and sun, but lacked the means. Instead, I planted six pines twenty years ago. I have heard that the pine embodies the integrity of a gentleman, yet these six gentlemen, dwelling on a poor farmer's land in a remote place, have never received a visit from any scholar of worth. You, sir, bear the reputation of a gentleman and have served as an official. Now you dwell here, dine here, and have shared these days with me for over a month. You have already built this shelter—would you not write a record to illuminate its spirit, to give voice to what lay unspoken, and thereby to honor the pavilion of a simple farmer?"

    I replied: "Though I was once recommended to office, I lack the conduct of a true gentleman and have been brought to banishment for it. Moreover, I am no master of the written word."

    The master said: "Do you deceive me? I know nothing of court affairs, yet I have seen many punished and dismissed by magistrates. Not all who are cast out are men without integrity, nor are all who escape censure truly gentlemen. It depends solely on whether one remains steadfast or yields. If you would use ornate and brilliant language to embellish the graceful beauty of peach and plum blossoms, that is not your nature, and I would not presume to ask it. But the straightforward character of pine and cypress through the cold seasons—this is what a gentleman delights to speak of and to write about. How much more so these six pines, which have endured for twenty years and only now encounter someone like you! To meet another such as you in days to come will be rare indeed. By the bond of righteousness, you cannot refuse this task."

    I was startled and moved, saying: "The master, though born and raised in the countryside and unlettered, speaks with such force and insight! There must be something in his nature that exceeds the common, something of the gentleman indeed."

    I drew the master close and spoke thus: "The number six, in the Book of Changes, represents the number of yielding darkness, and darkness takes constancy as its virtue. Many trees yield shadow, yet you chose the pine specifically, and of pines, precisely six. Thus you embody constancy upon constancy. Looking now at the ridge: from the east it extends for more than thirty li, rising abruptly in the flat plain before your house. Its form resembles a great platform, wide enough for dozens to sit. Six pines ring it about, and in the center stands one tree without lower branches, towering some twenty feet. At its crown the limbs spread thick and luxuriant, curving and reaching far. When viewed near, it appears as an umbrella unfurled; when seen from afar, like a great general standing in command, his standards raised, directing three armies.

    The Changes say: 'The army must have integrity like an elder—thus comes good fortune.' The commentators say 'elder' means one of venerable dignity. That you have positioned one supreme pine at the center represents this very image of the elder's constancy. Five pines ring the sides, no taller than six feet, their branches intertwined and spreading low, so that sitting beneath feels like resting within a fortified encampment, the ranks arrayed for the defense of the commander. The Changes say: 'The army is multitude; integrity is correctness. When multitude is governed by correctness, we achieve good fortune.' The commentators say this means winning the hearts of many to turn toward the right. Thus your arrangement of five humble pines at the borders embodies the constancy of the many.

    To the east lies Mount Tianshen, to the south Mount Xueshan, Mount Huangyi guards the west, and Mount Mieya embraces the north—all lofty peaks scattered at distances of ten to fifty li. From this pavilion, lifting one's gaze, all the craggy rocks, verdant woods, the changing aspects of the four seasons, and the shifting light and shadow of morning and evening mists lie within a single glance."

    The master then asked: "I have described the pavilion's form in full. But of your contemplation lodged in these pines and your spirit at ease in this shelter, I have heard much—why have you not spoken of a single scene?"

    I asked: "What scenes do you mean?"

    The master replied: "When night deepens and the moon shines clear, stepping through sparse shadows, the dancing shades blur and sway while songs rise faint and distant—you do not notice when night grows late. That is one scene. When rain falls soft and wind whispers cool, resting with the sound of wind through pines in your ears, now humming along, now mingling with the sound of sleep—you do not perceive when day departs westward. That is another scene. When the day is long and the breeze gentle, pine shadows lie upon the earth, no person to be seen in all directions, yet rare birds come and sing their strange calls while you, white-haired beneath your black cap, burn incense and sit in perfect stillness, becoming like a clay statue through the entire day. That is yet another scene. When farm laborers and rustic elders come bearing wine and gourds of liquor, thick wine and bean gruel mingled together, you draw them down to sit with you, drinking until drunk, sipping soup until sated—now uncapping your head, now loosening your robes and sitting with legs sprawled, disregarding courtesy and forgetting your form. That is another scene. That you have not spoken of these—is it not fear that people might mock you for so much inconstancy and lack of singular character?"

    I sighed: "Alas, the master speaks truth. Yet I alone have failed in constancy, and thus have come to this station. Now I speak of a gentleman's integrity and immediately follow with accounts of inconsistency—how can I not feel shame?"

    The master said further: "When you first arrived, your spirit was exhausted and your features worn thin. Since dwelling in this pavilion, though you have endured the triple-fold heat and late-summer warmth, no anxiety troubles your expression. The virtue the pines have shown you is not small—why then would you slight it?"

    I replied: "How could I forget? Yet the friendship of gentlemen is one where spirits meet and hearts merge, where breath resonates and the Way aligns—it need not be spelled out in words and writing."

    Then the master seated me in the center, called four farm companions to sit beside us, arranged wine and made a toast, requesting that I write this record. After six rounds of wine, I was deeply intoxicated. I wrote this account and presented it to the master.

    Among those seated, I am the oldest. The four guests all sit in a circle about the pavilion, their years and their integrity matching the master's own. The master is descended from a good family, of the surname Wu, and his name is Jingzhong.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Book of Changes' (Yijing) references throughout employ Confucian numerological and philosophical symbolism. The number six represents yin (receptive, feminine) energy and constancy; the 'elder' or 'man of authority' represents leadership and virtue.
    - The 'eight winds' refers to winds from all eight directions and represents a location of perfect geomantic balance.
    - The personal transformation described—from exhaustion to vitality, from anxiety to contentment—reflects Daoist and Neo-Confucian ideals of harmonizing with nature and achieving inner stillness.
    - The final scene of shared drinking and lowered proprieties between scholar and farmers represents a Daoist transcendence of social hierarchy through genuine human connection.
    - 'The pavilion itself functions as a microcosm: the central pine as the gentleman-leader, the five surrounding pines as loyal subjects, reflecting proper cosmic and social order.'
